			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Mezzing, Lulling, Looting - Questions From A Curious Bard<a name="13714"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Dec 23 03 1:39 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>You guys covered everything very well but I just have a couple of comments from my own experience. In LDoN groups keep a sharp eye out, if you can, try not to be the ML, despite the high CHA stopping to loot can make people antsy and you know what happens when the tanks get antsy... they try to pull, then out of nowhere you get a quick introduction to the business end of a huge train. Please please please communicate, as the others have touched on here, speak up, always tell the group whats going on, you cannot control what other people do but if you give them lots of information it can realy help contribute to the right decisions being made. I personally have a great ranger friend that I always do LDON with and he is awesome at pulling with me, Ill throw lulls down and he watches and pulls we have a great rythm but when we started we were horrible. It takes experience and time but its not bad once you do it 2 or 3 times, I was really nervous the first time I was asked to pull for LDoN and there are a lot of people out there who think bard pulling=death but what the h*ll do they know, theyve obviously never grouped with a capable bard. Also, pay heed to that little voice of caution you hear, if you cant decide whether 2 mobs are close enough to aggro each other, Lull them. If you think a caster is about to aggro an add, mez it, and if you think it's been a few since the last lull, reapply it. Don't listen to the people who rush rush rush, you will get high speed lulling and pulling down with experience, not by winging it and training your group because some impatient tank keeps saying &quot;pull pull pull&quot;. A capable bard can do anything but as soon as you fail to believe it, you will panic and inevitably be hacked into a pile of tonedeaf mush. It Really helps to be the puller and luller the first time someone asks you to lull, just communicate. Also I have to agree with the previous statements, tell the group you can mez up to three adds safely and let them know they will need to either off-tank the 4th add or root it or whatever. As far as outside encounters, it's really another story because you can handle an unlimited amount of adds outside but I'll skip that part at the risk of making this post rediculously longwinded. One more thing I found very helpful in sticky pulling situations, have a rogue sneak or someone with inside invis go into the room and target mobs for lulls, use /assist on them. 
<br />
   One more note of caution (pun intended) watch out for the coffins and pianos and stuff they often have mobs lying down inside them, so if you are pulling from near one its worth a peek to see if you need to lull something there, should help to avoid those nasty surprises. Dont forget if you are mezzing only one target you can switch targets for melee and your mezz will continue on the previous mob as long as you dont switch songs. 
<br />

<br />
Happy hunting. 
<br />
<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-7.gif" border="0" alt="Perplexed" hspace="2" /></span></td>
